# ASP.NET Framework → ASP.NET Core 8 Migration

## Key Architectural Changes

| Old (WebForms/MVC5) | New (ASP.NET Core 8) |
|---|---|
| `Response.End()` | Return `IActionResult` |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | Return `Redirect(url)` |
| `ThreadAbortException` pattern | **Eliminated entirely** |
| `Response.Write()` | Return `File()` / `Content()` |
| Event handlers (`btnExport_Click`) | Controller action methods |

## Migrated Code

```csharp
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Authorization;
using Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc;

public class ReportController : Controller
{
    private readonly ILogger<ReportController> _logger;

    public ReportController(ILogger<ReportController> logger)
    {
        _logger = logger;
    }

    // POST /Report/Export
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // File() handles Content-Disposition and terminates the response cleanly.
        // No Response.Clear(), no Response.End(), no ThreadAbortException.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    // POST /Report/Redirect
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult ProcessAndRedirect()
    {
        // Authentication is handled by middleware/attributes now,
        // but if you need manual checking:
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            return Redirect("/login");
            // No "endResponse" parameter — returning ends the action naturally.
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // NOTE: No ThreadAbortException catch needed — it doesn't exist in Core.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            _logger.LogError(ex, "Error processing request");
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }

    private string GenerateReport() => "Col1,Col2\nVal1,Val2";
    private void ProcessRequest() { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Better: Use `[Authorize]` Attribute

```csharp
[Authorize] // Replaces manual IsAuthenticated checks entirely
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Unauthenticated users are automatically redirected to the
    // login page configured in Program.cs
}
```

Configure in `Program.cs`:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddAuthentication(CookieAuthenticationDefaults.AuthenticationScheme)
    .AddCookie(options =>
    {
        options.LoginPath = "/login";   // Auto-redirect target
        options.AccessDeniedPath = "/denied";
    });
```

## Critical Pitfalls

### 1. `Response.End()` / `Response.Redirect(url, true)` Don't Exist
These relied on `Thread.Abort()` which is **removed from .NET Core**. Calling `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`. The entire pattern of "abort the thread to stop response processing" is gone — return an `IActionResult` instead.

### 2. Never Catch `ThreadAbortException` in Core
```csharp
// ❌ DEAD CODE in .NET Core — this exception is never thrown
catch (ThreadAbortException) { }
```
If you port this blindly, it compiles but the catch block is unreachable. Worse, it masks the architectural misunderstanding.

### 3. `Response.Write()` Still Exists But Don't Use It
```csharp
// ❌ Works but bypasses content negotiation, filters, and formatting
await Response.WriteAsync(data);
await Response.CompleteAsync(); // NOT equivalent to Response.End()

// ✅ Use IActionResult
return Content(data, "text/csv");
```

### 4. `Response.Clear()` Is Gone
In Core, the response stream hasn't been written to yet when your action runs (no buffering by default), so there's nothing to clear.

### 5. Post-Redirect Code Still Executes
```csharp
// ❌ In Framework, Response.Redirect(url, true) aborted the thread,
//    so code after it never ran. In Core, it DOES run:
Response.Redirect("/login");
DoSomethingElse(); // THIS EXECUTES in Core!

// ✅ Always return immediately
return Redirect("/login");
```

## Summary

The fundamental mindset shift: in ASP.NET Core, **you don't manipulate the response imperatively** — you **return a result object** that the framework renders. No thread aborts, no response clearing, no end signals.
